<p>The incretin drug pipeline extends well beyond semaglutide, tirzepatide, and retatrutide. Survodutide from Boehringer Ingelheim and mazdutide from Innovent Biologics/Eli Lilly represent two more dual-agonist approaches, each with a different receptor combination and a different clinical focus. Here's where each one stands.</p>

<h2>Survodutide: GLP-1 + Glucagon</h2>

<p>Survodutide (BI 456906) is a dual agonist targeting GLP-1 and glucagon receptors. This is a different pairing than tirzepatide (GLP-1 + GIP). Survodutide shares two of retatrutide's three targets but without the GIP component.</p>

<p>The inclusion of glucagon agonism is what makes survodutide interesting. Glucagon increases hepatic glucose output (which GLP-1 counterbalances) but also significantly increases energy expenditure and drives liver fat oxidation. In preclinical studies, the glucagon component made survodutide particularly effective at reducing liver fat, which has positioned it as a strong candidate for MASH (metabolic-associated steatohepatitis) treatment.</p>

<p><strong>Phase 2 data:</strong> In a trial of patients with MASH, survodutide at the highest dose (4.8mg weekly) produced significant improvement in liver histology, with up to 83% of patients showing MASH resolution at 48 weeks. Weight loss averaged 14.7% at the highest dose, comparable to semaglutide. Liver fat reduction was substantial, with some patients achieving near-complete elimination of hepatic steatosis.</p>

<p>The Phase 3 SYNCHRONIZE program is currently underway for both MASH and obesity indications. Boehringer Ingelheim has positioned survodutide primarily as a liver disease drug that also produces significant weight loss, rather than the other way around.</p>

<h2>Mazdutide: GLP-1 + Glucagon (Different Design)</h2>

<p>Mazdutide (IBI362, also known as LY3305677) is also a GLP-1/glucagon dual agonist, but with a different molecular design than survodutide. Developed by Innovent Biologics in collaboration with Eli Lilly, it has progressed furthest in Chinese clinical trials.</p>

<p><strong>Phase 3 data (China):</strong> The DREAM-BODY trial in Chinese adults with obesity showed 16.3% weight loss at the 6mg dose over 48 weeks. The 9mg dose produced even greater weight loss. These results are competitive with tirzepatide in the same population. Notably, mazdutide showed significant reductions in liver fat, waist circumference, and metabolic markers alongside the weight loss.</p>

<p>Mazdutide received conditional approval in China in 2024 for obesity treatment, making it the first GLP-1/glucagon dual agonist to reach any market. Chinese regulatory approval provides real-world usage data that other dual agonists still in trials can't offer.</p>

<h2>How They Compare to Existing Drugs</h2>

<p>The weight loss landscape is becoming crowded with mechanistically distinct options:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Semaglutide (GLP-1 only):</strong> ~15% weight loss. FDA approved. Gold standard baseline.</li>
<li><strong>Tirzepatide (GLP-1 + GIP):</strong> ~21% weight loss. FDA approved. Currently the most effective approved option.</li>
<li><strong>Survodutide (GLP-1 + glucagon):</strong> ~15% weight loss + strong liver effects. In Phase 3.</li>
<li><strong>Mazdutide (GLP-1 + glucagon):</strong> ~16% weight loss. Approved in China.</li>
<li><strong>Retatrutide (GLP-1 + GIP + glucagon):</strong> ~24% weight loss. In Phase 3.</li>
</ul>

<p>Survodutide and mazdutide don't beat tirzepatide on pure weight loss numbers. Their advantage is the glucagon-driven liver fat reduction, which makes them potentially better choices for patients whose primary concern is fatty liver disease (MASH/NAFLD) rather than maximum weight loss.</p>

<h2>The Liver Disease Angle</h2>

<p>MASH (previously NAFLD/NASH) affects an estimated 5-6% of the global adult population and is the fastest-growing cause of liver transplantation. Until 2024, there was no approved drug specifically for MASH. The GLP-1/glucagon dual agonists are positioned to fill this gap.</p>

<p>Glucagon's role in liver fat metabolism is well-established. It activates hepatic lipid oxidation (fat burning in the liver) and reduces lipogenesis (new fat formation in the liver). Combined with GLP-1's weight loss effects, the dual mechanism addresses both the systemic obesity that drives MASH and the hepatic fat accumulation that defines it.</p>

<p>Survodutide's Phase 2 MASH data (83% resolution rate) is among the strongest ever reported for any pharmaceutical intervention in liver disease. If the Phase 3 data confirms these results, survodutide could become a first-line treatment for MASH regardless of its weight loss efficacy.</p>

<h2>Timeline and Availability</h2>

<p>Mazdutide is available in China now. Global expansion depends on additional regulatory submissions and approvals in Western markets. Whether Eli Lilly's involvement (they have partnership rights outside China) leads to US/EU trials remains to be seen, given that Lilly already has tirzepatide and retatrutide in their pipeline.</p>

<p>Survodutide's Phase 3 trials are expected to produce results by late 2026 or 2027. If positive, FDA submission could follow within 6-12 months, with potential approval in 2028. Boehringer Ingelheim's focus on the MASH indication may accelerate regulatory review if the liver data is as strong as Phase 2 suggested.</p>

<p>For most patients in the US and EU today, these peptides are not yet accessible through legitimate channels. They represent the second wave of incretin-based therapies that will expand treatment options once they reach market. For researchers and clinicians tracking the obesity/liver disease space, survodutide and mazdutide are worth watching closely.</p>
